# Rollback Procedures

This document defines standards for automated rollback triggers, manual rollback steps, data migration rollback, and feature flag rollback.

---

## Automated Rollback Triggers

### When to Roll Back Automatically

| Trigger | Threshold | Action | Rationale |
|---------|------------|--------|-----------|
| Error rate | > 5% over baseline | Rollback | User impact |
| Latency P99 | > 2x baseline | Rollback | Degraded experience |
| Health check failure | 3 consecutive | Rollback | Instance unhealthy |
| Crash loop | 3 restarts in 5 min | Rollback | Application fault |
| Custom metric | Business-defined | Rollback or alert | Domain-specific |

### Implementation Pattern

```yaml
# Kubernetes deployment with rollback on failure
spec:
  progressDeadlineSeconds: 600
  revisionHistoryLimit: 10
  strategy:
    type: RollingUpdate
    rollingUpdate:
      maxSurge: 1
      maxUnavailable: 0
```

```yaml
# Argo Rollouts - automatic rollback on analysis failure
spec:
  analysis:
    templates:
    - templateName: success-rate
    args:
    - name: service-name
      value: my-service
  steps:
  - setWeight: 25
  - pause: {duration: 5m}
  - setWeight: 50
  - pause: {duration: 5m}
  - setWeight: 100
```

### Automated Rollback Checklist

- [ ] Rollback triggers are defined and documented
- [ ] Thresholds are tuned (not too sensitive, not too slow)
- [ ] Rollback is tested in staging
- [ ] Manual override exists for false positives
- [ ] Rollback does not cascade (e.g., rollback of rollback)
- [ ] Alerts fire when automatic rollback occurs

